<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-RatioRootTests" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Ratio and Root Tests</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction, remind that the <xref ref="thm-LimitComparisonTest" text="title"/> is super useful for rational functions and things that act like <xref ref="def-pSeries" text="title"/>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-EventuallyGeometricish">
    <title>Eventually Geometric-ish</title>
    <p>
        We'll look at series that act like geometric series, but first let's remind us what Geometric Series act like.
    </p>
    <xi:include href="./activities/act-ReminderGeometric.ptx" />
    <theorem xml:id="thm-RootTest">
      <title>Root Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\sum_{k=0}^\infty a_k</m> be an infinite series with <m>a_k\gt 0</m> for <m>k\geq 0</m> and consider <m>\lim_{k\to\infty} \sqrt[k]{a_k}</m>.
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                If there is some real number <m>r</m> with <m>r=\lim_{k\to\infty} \sqrt[k]{a_k}</m> and <m>0\leq r \lt 1</m>, then the series <m>\sum_{k=0}^\infty a_k</m> converges.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If there is some real number <m>r</m> with <m>r=\lim_{k\to\infty} \sqrt[k]{a_k}</m> and <m>r\gt</m> or if <m>\lim_{k\to\infty} \sqrt[k]{a_k}</m> does not exist, then the series <m>\sum_{k=0}^\infty a_k</m> diverges.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>\lim_{k\to\infty} \sqrt[k]{a_k}=1</m> then the Root Test fails and is inconclusive.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-RatioTest">
      <title>Ratio Test</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\sum_{k=0}^\infty a_k</m> be an infinite series with <m>a_k\gt 0</m> for <m>k\geq 0</m> and consider <m>\lim_{k\to\infty} \frac{a_{k+1}}{a_k}</m>.
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                If there is some real number <m>r</m> with <m>r=\lim_{k\to\infty} \frac{a_{k+1}}{a_k}</m> and <m>0\leq r \lt 1</m>, then the series <m>\sum_{k=0}^\infty a_k</m> converges.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If there is some real number <m>r</m> with <m>r=\lim_{k\to\infty} \frac{a_{k+1}}{a_k}</m> and <m>r\gt</m> or if <m>\lim_{k\to\infty} \frac{a_{k+1}}{a_k}</m> does not exist, then the series <m>\sum_{k=0}^\infty a_k</m> diverges.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>\lim_{k\to\infty} \frac{a_{k+1}}{a_k}=1</m> then the Root Test fails and is inconclusive.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

  </subsection>

</section>